# Clean Architecture Standards

## Core Principles

1. **Dependency Inversion**: Outer layers depend on inner layers, inner layers know nothing about outer layers
2. **Domain Core**: Domain layer is the core, depends on no external frameworks
3. **Interface Segregation**: Consumer defines interfaces, producer implements them
4. **Unidirectional Data Flow**: Data must be transformed when crossing layers

## Layer Definitions

| Layer | Responsibility | Dependency Rules |
|-------|---------------|------------------|
| Domain | Business entities, Value Objects, Aggregates, Business rules | No external dependencies |
| Application | Use case orchestration, Command/Query handling | Depends only on Domain |
| Infrastructure | Persistence, External services, Messaging | Implements Application interfaces |
| Interface | Web API, UI Controllers | Depends on Application |

## Prohibitions

- Domain layer must NOT import any framework classes (Spring, Jakarta, Hibernate, etc.)
- Domain layer must NOT use dependency injection
- Repository interfaces must be defined in Domain layer, implementations in Infrastructure layer
- Must NOT pass outer layer data structures (e.g., HTTP DTOs) into Domain layer

## Correct Examples

```java
// ✅ Domain layer: Pure Java, no framework dependencies
package com.ai.domain.model;

public class Order {
    private OrderId id;
    private Money totalAmount;

    public Money calculateShippingFee() {
        if (totalAmount.isGreaterThanOrEqual(Money.HUNDRED)) {
            return Money.ZERO;
        }
        return Money.of(10);
    }
}

// ✅ Application layer: Define repository interfaces
package com.ai.application.repository;

public interface OrderRepository {
    Optional<Order> findById(OrderId id);
    void save(Order order);
}

// ✅ Infrastructure layer: Implement repository
package com.ai.infrastructure.persistence;

@Repository
public class JpaOrderRepository implements OrderRepository {
    @Override
    public Optional<Order> findById(OrderId id) { ... }
}
```

## Incorrect Examples

```java
// ❌ Incorrect: Domain layer depends on Spring
package com.ai.domain.model;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;  // Forbidden!

@Component
public class Order { ... }

// ❌ Incorrect: Repository implementation in Domain layer
package com.ai.domain.repository;

public interface OrderRepository { ... }

// ❌ Incorrect: Domain layer depends on JPA annotations
package com.ai.domain.model;

import jakarta.persistence.*;  // Forbidden!

@Entity
public class Order { ... }

// ❌ Incorrect: Controller passes DTO directly to Domain
public void create(@RequestBody CreateOrderDto dto) {
    // dto contains Hibernate validation annotations, passed directly to Domain
    orderService.create(dto);  // Forbidden!
}
```

## Dependency Checks

Run architecture checks before committing:

```bash
# Check Domain layer has no framework dependencies
grep -r "import org.springframework" src/domain/ || echo "OK"
grep -r "import jakarta.persistence" src/domain/ || echo "OK"
grep -r "import javax.persistence" src/domain/ || echo "OK"

# Check TypeScript
grep -r "from '@angular'" src/domain/ || echo "OK"
```

## Violation Detection

The following patterns indicate Clean Architecture violations:

| Symptom | Problem |
|---------|---------|
| Domain class has `@Service`, `@Component` | Violates domain independence |
| Entity in `infrastructure` package | Violates layering |
| `new` to create Repository | Should be injected |
| Business logic in Controller | Violates separation of concerns |
